column1: 276080;instagram;2018-10-24 04:25:14;FALSE;"me: 15 minutes before my criminal injuries hearing began. this is what reclaiming a sense of belonging in the world looks like. ‚ô°

column3: i travelled back in time to rescue my 11
column5: all of whom were sexually assaulted. i did so via a criminal injuries compensation hearing
column6: which i filed a few years ago and have been working on since. i let my former selves know that i love them
column7: and as an adult i would do anything in my power to protect them and let that none of this was their fault; that they were good; clean and that they should feel no shame for all that they had endured. ‚ô°

column2: tbh.  i have since learned how enragingly common this multiple sexual assault thing is. i no longer feel ashamed of this identity because it has so little to do with me: it has to do with rapists and rape culture. so if you're out there feeling unbelievable due to being the common denominator
column3: i got u sis (or bro‚ô°); fuck the patriarchy cos' u normal.

column2: and started getting legal about this crap and broke down how much damage rape had cost me

column1: 276083;instagram;2018-10-24 04:25:51;FALSE;"i wrote this book of poetry to tell my story. my #metoo. when i was a child i was sexually abused by my parents friend. in college
column2: i finally went to therapy sessions for it and my therapist told me ""you need to find a way to heal the little girl inside of you"" so i did. i wrote out all the things i felt. all the things i kept to myself. all the shame
column4: the pain. but i also found some other things. i found my strength. my confidence. myself in these pages. this is page 167 of my book autopsy of me. available on amazon now

column1: in this day and age there has been so much talk of gender equality. i wanted to start this movement not as a hit towards the women that have gone through the tragedy of sexual assault but to show that men are also victims. we hear one side but in most media outlets we rarely hear about the other. the #himtoo movement is to give these men a voice to tell their story. we have seen a huge wave of sexual assualt accusations since the #metoo movement started. i am not doing this to compete with them
column2: in fact i do think that women that have been attacked should be able to take a stand. i stand against women that falsely accuse men and i believe these men should be able to take a stand aswell. in both situations acts like this can completely ruin lives and i want to see justice for the victims. accusations like this tend to stick even after being proven innocent. take the brett kavanaugh situation for example
column3: he was proven innocent and yet people still try to hold him as if he is guilty. i am holding this rally nov 17th in portland
column4: oregon for anyone that would like to come out and support. this is not a political event
column5: this is an event to fight the war on men. there should be equality through the genders but the more i here of gender equality the more it seems men being put down. for there to be equality it needs to be equal on both sides. those that commit this horrendous act should be punished just as those that bring these false pretenses.";;en;#HimToo

column1: 276217;instagram;2018-10-24 02:16:57;FALSE;"random acts of kindness mean the world to me. today i was gifted these items and their story is a treasure. they sat on two alters before making their way to me. the first was an alter at a womxn's sexual assault survivor group. these nature gems heard and created space for healing from trauma. they listened to stories
column3: rage and tears. they touched the hands of survors.

column1: as birds of a feather will have it
column2: these three items sat on another alter.

column1: the second was an alter at a men's prison. these items created space in an incarcerated person's support group. these items heard the story of how one inmate became convicted. he committed the crime of sexual assault. he cried
column2: expressed true regret and honest shame. he did not know where these items came from before and he did not need to. these roses and this feather
column3: brought with them the stories from the previous alter and impacted the room within that prison. then
column5: they were gifted to me while teaching a group of college students about consent.

column1: this remains one of the hardest things i have ever done. writing this piece took me back to a very dark place in my life
column2: & though i am proud & grateful to have survived it
column3: it is not something i generally speak about willingly. is it shame? partly. though i have nothing to feel ashamed of. i weighed the knowledge that in putting this out into a public forum
column4: i would be opening myself up to scrutiny from complete strangers & also from people that i know. that i‚Äôm opening up about something so private. that my children will one day know what happened to me.

column1: but then i realized that though it is private
column2: it is also something that happens to too many people
column3: & if it has been painful for me to keep silent about my secret
column4: then so it also must be for others. i realized that when we keep silent
column5: the only ones who benefit are our attackers. i want to help end the stigma around sexual assault. yes
column6: speaking out is hard. but it‚Äôs for something bigger than myself
column7: & if i can give even one survivor of sexual assault the courage they need to break their silence
column8: then it was worth it. it‚Äôs worth it just to open people‚Äôs eyes to the reality & frequency of sexual assault. and also
column9: to educate. it is frightening how little people know about the facts & statistics of sexual assault.

column1: so i ask humbly that you take the time to read the piece that i wrote for my blog
column2: entitled ‚Äúopinion: the epidemic of sexual assault & why we need to stop keeping silent.‚Äù i ask you to consider my words & the statistics that i have put forward. and lastly
column3: that if you or someone you know is a survivor of sexual assault
column4: please know that you are not alone. we stand together on this. you don‚Äôt have to feel ashamed or afraid. and please
column6: ask for help. here are the numbers for support in the u.s. & canada:

for the united states call the national sexual assault hotline: 800.656.hope (4673)

column1: in order to stay motivated i need to understand why i am this size.
when i was around 7 years old i moved to a new special needs primary school. there was this one teaching assistant who was well liked by teachers and other ta's.
this teaching assistant had a weird obsession with healthy eating
column2: and she projected that onto us pupils. i was verbally abused by her. for example if we didn't eat healthily enough at lunch she would call us ""little fatties"". now
column3: you might think i was just a snowflake
column4: but i was an 8 year old vulnerable autistic child
column5: already slightly overweight being called a fatty. it didn't make me want to eat healthily
column6: it made me do the opposite. and i did the opposite for around 14 years til i ballooned to 19.11 stone (266lbs). she would also call me other names
column7: like when she whispered ""you've got greasy hair"" to me in assembly and made me cry in front of the entire school. she did nothing to comfort me.

column1: from then on i associated being healthy and excercising with punishment
column2: so i overate and eventually became morbidly obese. you can see my weight gain in these pictures. i was the same weight as my mum at 10 years old (10 stone). that's the weight i should be now.
i've come to learn that being healthy doesn't have to be a bad thing
column4: i don't have to do what that ta said
column6: healthily. i've learned it doesn't have to be punishment.

column2: i do regret not letting my mum report this woman
column3: but i was so scared they would do nothing about it
column4: and that she would abuse me even more if she found out i ratted her.

column1: 276800;instagram;2018-10-23 18:38:03;FALSE;"i wrote my first poem on september 12
column2: 2001 during a new class activity that my english teacher designed for us in the wake of the events that transpired the day prior as a means of personal reflection.  we began journaling for the first ten minutes of each class period and i believe that we had this class every other day
column4: this piece was likely written september 14
column5: 2001.  it is a poem about my step-father
column6: the man who raped me for seven years of my childhood.  this is actually when the abuse stopped after enduring the most intense period throughout the summer prior.  i find it rather fascinating that a twelve year old girl could write something like this and not be questioned about its contents...however
column7: i am grateful for the safety i discovered within the convolutions and metaphors of poetry that have served to liberate me from the trauma induced psychosis of my early life experiences.

column1: something broke in me and i no longer feel compelled to hide behind my healing. i am a storyteller and this is presently the trajectory of my story
column2: healing the pieces of myself as they present themselves clearly. and so
column3: i am choosing transparency and unhinged honesty as i alchemize my broken heart into the art that seeps from these hands.

column1: i have a poetry series i will be launching soon titled 'gathering bones' that will be a whole new venture for me. stay tuned!
don't forget to visit my blog to peep more of my writings

column1: 276804;instagram;2018-10-23 18:38:51;FALSE;this is what i was not ready for but today saw one video that forced me to speak on what have happened with me... the video forced me to speak on my smallest scar too!! i am brought up in a protected and safe manner..... so no such kinda thing ever happened with me before this day.. i was 15 years old and me with my family and friends were on hyderabad trip.. our last stop was mysore and we were enjoying our last hours in mysore's vrundavan garden.... we were returning after watching fountain show with the crowd of almost 2000 people.. i don't know how but i got separate from my group and family in midst of the crowd and started searching for them .... i remember i was wearing a pink mini one piece and when i was searching for them suddenly one hand touched my hips... i ignored thinking it was by mistake by someone but again same thing happened twice to thrice then i look back but found no one who could do such ridiculous behavior... then i started walking fast in search of my parents but then again that hand tried to pull off my dress from below and started misbehaving with me... this was height which i cannot tolerate... so first i grab his hand and turn around and slap him 3-4 times on his face and just pushed him on the ground and started walking as nothing happened.... the crowd was just staring and standing cold handed... then after 10 minutes anyhow i found my parents but this whole incident is not known to them till date... i was strong enough not to tolerate any kind of non sense of anyone but not to tell my parents what happened with me... till today also they don't know what had happened in those 15-20 minutes... and i don't want them to know this but i wrote this just because i want to tell girls or women that don't ever tolerate any kind of misbehaviour with you in any damn terms... even though the guy is your best friend but then also certain limits should never be crossed in talking as well as physical terms... be brave and strong and never be quiet for any such thing ever happened with you!!!! #metoomovement #metoo #bebrave #strong #speak #berude #metooindia;;en;#metoomovement

the me too movement is an unconventional republican talking point
in the growing and hotly debated #metoo movement at both the state and federal levels
column2: some california district candidates are using the issue as a campaign strategy to attack their opponent. interestingly enough

for those who don‚Äôt know our story... we tried for years to conceive again. from disappointing doctors visits to practically giving up hope ‚Äì that stage was in itself heartbreaking at times. but with some self inquiry
column5: and help from my teachers i was able to finally accept the fact that i was not meant to conceive again. however
column6: within about a month of this radical acceptance i had lost a dear friend to cancer and spent a week myself in the hospital. from gut-wrenching grief sprouted a tiny miracle within me. a burst of life force energy began to implant itself in my womb. i was delighted with joy and gratitude. i spent most of my pregnancy in disbelief of how the stars had finally aligned
column7: that the universe finally answered my prayers.

column2: inc. hosts art drop for sexual violence awareness

column3: inc. (pathways) a nonprofit organization dedicated to ending the silence and ending sexual violence is hosting an ‚Äúart drop‚Äù project kick-off on 10/24/18 between 10am-12pm in worcester

column1: purpose: ‚Äòart drop‚Äô was created by pathways for change (serving central ma)
column2: to help counter recent messaging that perpetuates victim blaming & triggers trauma.

column1: the ‚Äòart drop‚Äô kick-off participants will leave (drop) over 100 small canvas paintings (4‚Äù x 4‚Äù squares) created by staff
column3: survivors and allies as a way to spread a message to survivors that we hear them
column4: we believe them and they are not alone.

column1: pathways has been supporting survivors of sexual violence for 45 years (est. 1973). while they are proud of the work they do
column2: they also realize how much more work there is to be done. pathways staff
column3: interns and volunteers are standing up
column4: stepping out and taking up arms (in the form of paintbrushes!); to get the word out that ‚Äòwe believe survivors‚Äô! on the morning of wednesday
column6: pathways ‚Äòart drop‚Äô kick-off members will disperse throughout worcester
column9: secretly placing art pieces (with messages of hope along with information and their toll free hotline number) to be found by others. pathways hopes that whoever finds an ‚Äòart drop‚Äô canvas piece will then share on social media where they found the ‚Äòart drop‚Äô canvas (maybe a photo too!) and what it means to them

column2: professional squash player maria toorpakay wazir shares her story of growing up in a pakistani village known for being one of the most dangerous places on earth. at the age of 4

column1: old vag club x magdaladies: bystander intervention
come along to explore several important  questions from the #metoo era such as:
- what is bystander intervention? - how can you deal with a situation with which you are not entirely comfortable?
- why does society place onus on the victim and what can we do to change this?
